👉 What is Idempotency in Backend Systems? 🖥️ 
--------------------------------------------

Let’s understand this simply.

Imagine a light switch 💡

Turn it ON once → Light turns ON 
Turn it ON again → Still ON 

Nothing changes after the first action.

That is idempotent behavior.

Now imagine clicking “Pay ₹1000” 💳 twice.

First click → ₹1000 deducted 
Second click → ₹1000 deducted again 

That is NOT idempotent.

In backend terms:

An operation is idempotent if 
making the same request multiple times 
produces the same result as making it once.

No additional side effects.

Why does this matter?

Because networks fail.

• Client times out 
• User refreshes page 
• Request is retried 
• Server responds late 

If your API is not idempotent, you risk:

• Duplicate payments 
• Double orders 
• Repeated database updates 
• Data inconsistency 

Now let’s connect this to HTTP methods.

GET → Idempotent 
PUT → Idempotent 
DELETE → Idempotent 
POST → Usually NOT idempotent 

Why?

PUT replaces a resource. 
Calling it again keeps the same final state.

POST usually creates new resources. 
Calling it again creates duplicates.

But here’s the important part:

POST can be made idempotent.

How to Solve Idempotency Problems 👇

1️⃣ Idempotency Keys 

Client sends a unique key with the request. 
Server stores the key and result. 

If the same key is received again → 
Return previous response instead of processing again.

Common in payment systems like Stripe.

2️⃣ Database Unique Constraints 

Use unique fields (e.g., orderId, transactionId). 
If duplicate request comes → database prevents duplication.

3️⃣ Upsert Logic 

Instead of “create new”, 
use insert-or-update pattern.

4️⃣ Proper HTTP Method Usage 

Use PUT when updating known resources. 
Use POST carefully for creation.

5️⃣ Request Deduplication Layer 

Store request fingerprints in cache (Redis) 
and block duplicates within a time window.

Golden Rule 🧠 

If a user retries a request, 
your system should not panic.

Design APIs so repeated requests don’t break your data.






